This was followed by a social descent.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
For a long time, Green was treated in psychiatry.
During much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived on the street for a time, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent a while in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 to a Jewish working-class family in Bethnal Green, London.
At a young age, he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven, he learned the first guitar grips.
At the age of 15 the teenager started playing the guitar professionally and was given the chance to be on stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton in the Bluesbreakers.
In the middle of the Blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 with his bluesbreaker colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross" composed by Green gave the group the first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted it to the lead of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its dark side: Green did not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that happened to me in life is the drugs - the best was to land a number one hit."
Towards the end of the decade in 1979, Green surprisingly succeeded in winning a respect with an album inspired by religious themes.
Meanwhile, Fleetwood Mac swam without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a bigger comeback until he started in 1996 with a group of musicians friends.
The British Daily Telegraph spoke at the time of a rock star who had returned to the earth.
Free from Drogen released Green with the Peter Green Splinter Group, until the band disbanded in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his soft sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
